                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d384">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">368.1121 Stephano, Christopher/3: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-15T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 15, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 16—5:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>39. My telegram No. 34, March 10, 9 p.m. Pistolaki was in hiding here and not
                    with the fleet and has now surrendered himself to the authorities. Stephano
                    seemed about to be released today when he unaccountably volunteered to the
                    examiner that Pistolaki had received a letter from Venizelos a few days before
                    the outbreak and that he knew this because he himself was with Pistolaki in the
                    latter’s house at the time. He is accordingly still under detention but being
                    treated with leniency.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
